=E2=80=9CEvery banker knows that if he has to prove that he is worthy of cr=
edit, however good may be his arguments, in fact his credit is gone,=E2=80=
=9D but here=E2=80=99s this:

The bleeding stopped only after the bank offered some major depositors a lo=
ok inside its operations in exchange for signing nondisclosure arrangements=
. Some took up on the offer.
=E2=80=9CI feel for the depositors =E2=80=94 they didn=E2=80=99t sign up to=
 be bank equity analysts,=E2=80=9D Mr. Gibbons said.

That is from a  New York Times story=C2=A0by Rob Copeland=C2=A0about how We=
stern Alliance Bancorp weathered this year=E2=80=99s regional banking crisi=
s, in which depositors got nervous about the balance sheets of many smaller=
 banks and started pulling their money out. And Western Alliance=E2=80=99s =
approach was, roughly, that=C2=A0people showed up to take their money out, =
and chief financial officer Dale Gibbons pulled them into a room and said =
=E2=80=9Clook, don=E2=80=99t share this with anyone, but here is everything=
 we know about our business, we=E2=80=99re gonna walk through our loans one=
 by one to satisfy you that we are solvent so you leave your money here.=E2=
=80=9D It=E2=80=99s like the=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s a Wonderful Life bank run=C2=
=A0scene, except that instead of saying =E2=80=9Cthe money=E2=80=99s not he=
re, why your money=E2=80=99s in Joe=E2=80=99s house, that=E2=80=99s right n=
ext to yours, and in the Kennedy house, and Mrs. Maitland=E2=80=99s house, =
and a hundred others,=E2=80=9D George Bailey pulls each depositor aside and=
 says =E2=80=9Cthe money=E2=80=99s not here, why your money=E2=80=99s in Jo=
e=E2=80=99s house, he=E2=80=99s got a 730 FICO and has never missed a payme=
nt and prices are up 14% in his neighborhood so the LTV is now at 63%, and =
in the Kennedy house, and Kennedy just got a raise at work so his payments =
are now down to 23% of his income, and Mrs. Maitland=E2=80=99s=E2=80=9D unt=
il the depositors=E2=80=99 eyes glaze over and they say =E2=80=9Cokay fine,=
=C2=A0whatever, I=E2=80=99ll leave my money here.=E2=80=9D
You see Bagehot=E2=80=99s point, though. If your bank is sitting you down a=
nd making you sign a nondisclosure agreement to tell you details of its ope=
rations=C2=A0to keep your deposits, something has gone very wrong. Not nece=
ssarily with the bank =E2=80=94=C2=A0apparently what Western Alliance=E2=80=
=99s depositors saw satisfied them that the bank was fine,=C2=A0deposits st=
abilized and the stock is up =E2=80=94=C2=A0but with general confidence in =
the banking system.
This is the basic problem of regional banks. Bank depositors didn=E2=80=99t=
 sign up to be bank equity analysts. Bank deposits are supposed to be   inf=
ormation-insensitive; a dollar in a bank account is just supposed to be wor=
th a dollar. Nobody is supposed to sign an NDA to review non-public financi=
al information (or even flip through a 10-K to read public financial inform=
ation) just to open a bank account. But if you are not conducting detailed =
due diligence on your bank, how do you know that your deposits at the bank =
are safe?
You are, in essence, trusting=C2=A0the banking system, which often means tr=
usting=C2=A0the government=E2=80=99s regulation and supervision of banks. I=
n the US, if you have $250,000 or less in the bank,
  [1]
=C2=A0you are pretty explicitly trusting the government: The US Federal Dep=
osit Insurance Corp. insures all bank deposits up to $250,000 per depositor=
 per bank, so you don=E2=80=99t really need to care about how good or bad y=
our bank=E2=80=99s business is. If you have much more than $250,000 in the =
bank, then your trust in the system and the government is more implicit and=
 vibes-based. =E2=80=9CThe US government wouldn=E2=80=99t let me lose all t=
he money that I need to run my business,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cthe US govern=
ment wouldn=E2=80=99t let the banking system collapse,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=
=9Cthe US banking system is highly regulated and politically salient, and s=
urely the US government would not allow my bank to take dumb risks with my =
money, so I=E2=80=99m sure its balance sheet is fine and I won=E2=80=99t bo=
ther looking at it.=E2=80=9D
  [2]

And so the government is in charge of making sure all the banks are fine. T=
here are problems with this. One is that there are a lot of banks, and it i=
s hard for the government to know what they=E2=80=99re all up to.=C2=A0Anot=
her problem is that the many small banks,=C2=A0because they are smaller, ar=
e regulated less strictly than the few big banks:

These lenders have long pitched themselves as the crux of the U.S. economy,=
 doling out loans and financing to small businesses that would otherwise be=
 ignored. They hold roughly two-thirds of all deposits in rural areas.
These banks receive relatively lax treatment from regulators, who require t=
hem to disclose less about their finances and set aside less money as a buf=
fer against deposit runs, compared with their larger counterparts.

A third problem is moral hazard: There are 4,100 banks and, before this yea=
r, most depositors kind of thought they were equally safe, because the depo=
sitors weren=E2=80=99t doing any due diligence. And the government regulate=
s them all to make sure that they behave prudently, but with 4,100 banks th=
e government can only pay so much attention to any one regional bank. If yo=
u are a bank, the more risk you take, the more money you can make, and you =
can invest some of that money in attracting deposits (by paying higher depo=
sit rates, or by doing more marketing, or by making loans and providing ser=
vices to build relationships that bring in deposits). If everyone is treate=
d as equally risky, there is a tendency for deposits to flow to the riskies=
t banks. Copeland=E2=80=99s article begins with this horrifying anecdote:

Every quarter for the past several years, Ken Vecchione printed out a sprea=
dsheet comparing the growth of the bank he runs, Western Alliance, with its=
 three principal competitors: First Republic, Signature Bank and Silicon Va=
lley Bank.
And each time, Mr. Vecchione was annoyed because the analysis would show th=
at Western Alliance=E2=80=99s loans and deposits were growing similarly to =
the others =E2=80=94 its total assets tripled in five years =E2=80=94 but i=
ts stock price wasn=E2=80=99t soaring as high.
=E2=80=9CWe were, I have to admit, a bit envious of them,=E2=80=9D said Mr.=
 Vecchione, who has been chief executive of the Phoenix bank since 2018.

First Republic, Signature and Silicon Valley Bank are all gone now: If you =
are a bank and you are growing faster than other banks, there=E2=80=99s a p=
retty good chance that it=E2=80=99s because you=E2=80=99re taking more risk=
 than other banks.
Vecchione =E2=80=9Csaid he had been asking regulators lately, =E2=80=98Do y=
ou even want us to exist?=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s a fair question
  [3]
:=C2=A0

Government officials can=E2=80=99t seem to decide what they want banks like=
 Western Alliance to do. Since the 2008 financial crisis, policymakers have=
 put the brakes on =E2=80=9Ctoo big to fail=E2=80=9D institutions, saying t=
hey would prefer risk to be distributed more evenly across lenders. Now, th=
ough, there is skepticism about the grow-at-all-costs ambitions of smaller =
banks, and hints of an openness to mergers between lenders.
In a private meeting last month with bank chiefs, including Jamie Dimon of =
JPMorgan, Treasury Secretary Janet L. Yellen said she would welcome more le=
nders merging with one another, according to a person who participated in t=
he briefing, in part because it would make it easier for regulators to cond=
uct oversight.

After 2008, there was a perception that the government was implicitly guara=
nteeing the biggest banks, and that this was bad; the reaction was to regul=
ate the biggest banks more strictly, to try to prevent them from becoming b=
igger, and to favor smaller regional banks. After the 2023 crisis, there is=
 a realization that=C2=A0the government is implicitly guaranteeing all of t=
he banks. And if you are in that business anyway, you will prefer to guaran=
tee a few big, well-capitalized, closely supervised banks rather than thous=
ands of risky ones.

