      Shell
   =20
 =20

A curious fact of the modern energy industry is that there is significant o=
verlap between climate-focused environmental, social and governance investo=
rs, who want oil companies to drill less oil for environmental reasons, and=
 regular old money-focused investors, who want oil companies to drill less =
oil for financial reasons. In the US shale boom, whenever oil prices rose, =
oil companies did a ton of investment to find new wells and produce more oi=
l, and the result was that prices went down and drillers kept losing money.=
 And what economically minded investors learned from that is that, when oil=
 prices go up and oil companies make more money, the companies should=C2=A0=
do share buybacks=C2=A0and give the money back to investors, rather than sp=
end it on oil wells that will just drive the price down.=C2=A0
Meanwhile, if you are focused mainly on climate change, and you invest in o=
il companies, and oil prices go up and oil companies make money, you=C2=A0a=
lso=C2=A0do not want them to spend the money drilling more oil wells. Your =
preference will be for them to spend the money on, like, shutting down the =
oil wells, capping them securely, and then building wind farms. But stock b=
uybacks are better than more oil wells.
  [4]
=C2=A0
Significant overlap, but still some differences. The Wall Street Journal  r=
eports on Shell Plc:

Shell said Wednesday that it will share billions more from its record profi=
ts with investors while deepening its commitment to the oil-and-gas busines=
ses that produce the highest returns. ...
In its release, the company said it will launch share buybacks of at least =
$5 billion for the second half of 2023. It will also cut spending, keep its=
 oil production steady and scale back on less-profitable businesses.
=E2=80=9CWe will invest in the models that work=E2=80=94those with the high=
est returns that play to our strengths,=E2=80=9D said Sawan in a statement.=
=C2=A0=E2=80=A6
Shell had set a target of reducing by 1% to 2% annually its production of l=
iquids, a category including oil. The company, which previously said it had=
 reached its broader goals related to the plan sooner than anticipated, on =
Wednesday said that it would no longer seek those annual reductions.

And   Bloomberg News reports:

The shift in how the company invests reflects a reset of its strategy, whic=
h seeks to focus on businesses that generate the highest returns =E2=80=94 =
and shed those that don=E2=80=99t perform. It=E2=80=99s part of a pitch tha=
t Shell=E2=80=99s new Chief Executive=C2=A0Wael Sawan=C2=A0made on Wall St.=
 Wednesday as he tries to convince investors the company=E2=80=99s valuatio=
n should be closer to that of its more fossil fuel-focused American rivals.=
=C2=A0
Overall, Shell will cut its capital expenditure to $22 billion to $25 billi=
on a year for 2024 and 2025, down from an expectation of $23 billion to $27=
 billion this year. While the overall number shrinks, the amount going to t=
he company=E2=80=99s core oil and gas business will stay steady, increasing=
 its share of the pie.=C2=A0
Shell channeled about 48% of last year=E2=80=99s cash capital expenditure i=
nto its integrated gas and upstream divisions, which pump oil and ship liqu=
efied natural gas around the world. That share will grow to between 52% and=
 59% in 2024 and 2025, the company said in a presentation on Wednesday.=C2=
=A0
Even as it made this strategic shift, Shell reiterated the climate targets =
made under former CEO=C2=A0Ben van Beurden, including a goal to reach net z=
ero carbon by 2050. But the presentation made only one mention of that goal=
 and didn=E2=80=99t present a clear plan to achieve it.

If you are money-focused, you might like=C2=A0flat oil production, reduced =
non-oil capex and higher buybacks. If you are climate-focused, you would pr=
efer lower oil production and more clean-energy investment, but flat capex =
and higher buybacks are still probably better than more exploration.
I should say that there is a third perspective. You could be a person who w=
ants oil companies to drill more oil wells, even if it reduces profits. You=
 might want this because reducing the price of oil is good for consumers, o=
r because drilling more oil wells is good for oil-industry=C2=A0employment,=
 or because reducing the price of oil has good=C2=A0geopolitical=C2=A0effec=
ts, or because you are a politician and can make some political hay by crit=
icizing =E2=80=9Cwoke=E2=80=9D ESG investing. Many people quite reasonably =
believe one or more of these things; in the US, both  Republican and  Democ=
ratic politicians have called on oil companies to drill more oil because th=
ey believe, for one reason or another, that doing so would be=C2=A0good for=
 America.
But on the particular question of oil-company capital expenditures, the =E2=
=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D position is sometimes aligned with the =E2=80=9Cruthless=
 profit maximization=E2=80=9D position, and the =E2=80=9Canti-ESG=E2=80=9D =
position is sometimes on the other side. We have   talked before about a st=
range letter that Louisiana=E2=80=99s state treasurer sent last year to Bla=
ckRock Inc., pulling some Louisiana state funds out of BlackRock because he=
 thought BlackRock was too ESG. =E2=80=9CSimply put, we cannot be party to =
the crippling of our own economy,=E2=80=9D he wrote, meaning that ESG inves=
tment would have the effect of reducing oil and gas drilling in Louisiana. =
But he also wrote that ESG investing =E2=80=9Cis contrary to Louisiana law =
on fiduciary duties, which requires a sole focus on financial returns for t=
he beneficiaries of state funds.=E2=80=9D You can=E2=80=99t have it both wa=
ys! Sometimes drilling more oil is good for oil-industry workers and bad fo=
r oil-company=C2=A0financial returns. If you want to maximize financial ret=
urns, sometimes you have to drill less oil.

