   =20
      SAFU
   =20
 =20

A core concept in the crypto financial system is the box. This is not an of=
ficial term or anything, but it=E2=80=99s how I think of it; the term   com=
es from something that Sam Bankman-Fried said to me on a podcast. Here=E2=
=80=99s how it works:
=09You start some project or business or blockchain or whatever.=09You issu=
e a token for the project. The token may or may not have some sort of claim=
 on the cash flows of the project, or some governance rights over it, but i=
n any case it is the token=C2=A0of=C2=A0the project, and its price will flu=
ctuate based on people=E2=80=99s perception of the project, their expectati=
ons for its future, its actual success, etc. The price of the token will re=
flect the value of the project in some loose way.=09You give yourself a lot=
 of the token.=09You multiply the trading price of the token (which reflect=
s the market value of the project) times the number of tokens that you have=
 (which is probably large, since you made up the token and can give yoursel=
f as much as you want), and you get a large dollar number.=09You probably c=
annot=C2=A0sell your tokens for that large dollar number: If you dumped all=
 your tokens at once, confidence in the project would fall, supply would sw=
amp demand, the price of the token would collapse and you probably wouldn=
=E2=80=99t get very much money for your stash.=09But you can turn the token=
s into money in other ways. You can borrow against them; if you say =E2=80=
=9Chey I have $10=C2=A0billion of tokens=E2=80=9D some crypto lender might =
give you a $5 billion secured loan.=09More broadly, you can say =E2=80=9CI =
am a billionaire, what with my $10 billion of tokens,=E2=80=9D and people w=
ill tend to trust you more and give you more economic opportunities because=
 you=E2=80=99re a billionaire. If you put in a bid to buy a mansion or a sp=
orts team or whatever, people will take you seriously because you have $10 =
billion (of tokens). If your bid is successful, a bank will probably lend y=
ou the money to buy the mansion or sports team. The loan will not necessari=
ly be=C2=A0secured by=C2=A0your $10 billion pile of tokens, but the bank=E2=
=80=99s credit decision will probably be like =E2=80=9Cthis person has $10 =
billion, she=E2=80=99s good for this loan.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=09And people will=
 be more willing to deal with=C2=A0your project =E2=80=94=C2=A0or business =
or blockchain or whatever, the thing that started all of this =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0because there=E2=80=99s $10 billion behind it. =E2=80=9CI will trade on =
this crypto exchange without worrying about it getting hacked, because if i=
t gets hacked surely it will make up my losses, because it has $10 billion.=
=E2=80=9D

This is not something that crypto invented, or that is limited to crypto.=
=C2=A0Lots of people found regular companies, issue stock of those companie=
s, keep a lot of stock for themselves, and either explicitly borrow against=
 that stock (margin loans, etc.) or at least point to their huge pile of st=
ock as proof that they are rich and leverage that wealth to buy other thing=
s.=20
Carl Icahn has margin loans against his Icahn Enterprises stock. Elon Musk =
has margin loans against his Tesla Inc. stock; also, though, he was clearly=
 able to get financing to buy Twitter Inc. (not=C2=A0secured by his Tesla s=
tock) because banks were like =E2=80=9Cyeah, this guy=E2=80=99s rich, we=E2=
=80=99ll lend him money even if we think that the Twitter deal is kind of a=
 dog.=E2=80=9D
Nor is any of this really=C2=A0wrong; I am not necessarily describing a fra=
ud or a mistake or anything. It just sort of depends on what the project is=
? The problem is that a lot of stuff in crypto is a=C2=A0pure=C2=A0confiden=
ce business: Tesla makes cars, and if people lost confidence in its stock t=
here would still be cars, but many crypto projects just make crypto trades,=
 and if people lost confidence in their crypto trades there=E2=80=99d be no=
thing left. It is a very wrong-way risk; the pile of money safeguarding you=
r business evaporates in exactly the circumstances that your business is in=
 trouble.
The other problem is that at least some people in crypto were=C2=A0very=C2=
=A0self-aware of this dynamic. It is one thing to start a car company, issu=
e stock to finance factories, keep stock for yourself as the founder, get r=
ich on paper, and then borrow against your vast stock wealth to finance a r=
ocket company or whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0each decision there is plausibly a=
bout building a real business. It is another thing to think =E2=80=9Chey I=
=E2=80=99m gonna issue some tokens because if I can get people to buy them =
I can borrow a lot of money and walk away from the mess.=E2=80=9D There is =
adverse selection there. I am not saying everyone in crypto thought that. I=
 am just saying that Sam Bankman-Fried=C2=A0explicitly described that thoug=
ht process to me as a general feature of crypto, and look how that worked o=
ut.
The most classic cases of the box are:
=09
 Terra was a blockchain, it issued tokens (called Luna), the tokens went up=
, and it used them to collateralize=C2=A0billions of dollars of a stablecoi=
n called TerraUSD. Confidence in Luna dropped and billions of dollars of Te=
rraUSD vanished in like a week.=C2=A0=09
 FTX was Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s=C2=A0crypto exchange, Alameda Research=
 was his crypto trading firm, FTX issued tokens (called FTT, though there w=
ere also some other =E2=80=9CSamcoins=E2=80=9D called SRM and MAPS and stuf=
f), and Alameda used them to collateralize billions of dollars of loans =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0from outside lenders, and later from FTX, using its customers=
=E2=80=99 money. Confidence in the tokens dropped, Alameda went extremely b=
ankrupt, and billions of dollars of FTX customer money vanished in like a w=
eek.=C2=A0

One feature of the box is that you can sort of earn your way out of it. If =
your project is successful and makes a lot of money, or if it is successful=
 enough to allow you to=C2=A0sell a lot of your tokens over time, you will =
end up with a lot of actual money, dollars or whatever that you own free an=
d clear. And then when people say =E2=80=9CI trust this person because she =
has $10 billion=E2=80=9D they will be, in some more robust sense, correct. =
The people running Terra understood this, and built up a war chest of non-L=
una money (Bitcoin, dollars, etc.) to back TerraUSD. They just didn=E2=80=
=99t do enough of it before confidence collapsed.
None of this quite describes  the SAFU fund, but it kind of rhymes:

Binance, the world=E2=80=99s largest crypto exchange, set up an emergency f=
und in 2018 to reassure customers their digital assets would be safe. Now t=
hat federal regulators have zeroed in on Binance, its rainy day fund has fa=
llen in value by 11%.
The fund was valued at nearly $950 million at the start of the month, accor=
ding to blockchain addresses that Binance says hold the assets. After the S=
ecurities and Exchange Commission sued Binance last week, it fell to some $=
840 million.
The fund=E2=80=94dubbed the secure asset fund for users, or SAFU for short=
=E2=80=94is meant to cover losses from hacks or other compromises of Binanc=
e=E2=80=99s systems. Changpeng Zhao, Binance=E2=80=99s founder, has also me=
ntioned it in times of stress to give comfort to users, including when riva=
l FTX collapsed. It holds a combination of bitcoin, dollar-pegged cryptocur=
rencies and a coin created by Binance, BNB.
That token, BNB, plays an outsize role in SAFU=E2=80=94accounting for rough=
ly half the dollar value.=C2=A0
BNB has tumbled more than 20% after the SEC suit alleged that Binance=E2=80=
=99s overseas company operated an illegal trading platform in the U.S. and =
misused customers=E2=80=99 funds.=C2=A0

The SAFU (=E2=80=9Csafu=E2=80=9D is sort of crypto slang for =E2=80=9Csafe=
=E2=80=9D) is  funded by Binance trading fees; it is=C2=A0mostly=C2=A0a cas=
e of taking real earnings from the business and keeping them in real money =
(some dollars, mostly Bitcoin). But a big chunk of the fund=C2=A0is=C2=A0in=
 Binance=E2=80=99s own token, and when Binance has an emergency that is bad=
 for the value of its emergency fund.

