   =20
      Has Elon Musk defeated Twitter=E2=80=99s spam bots?
   =20
 =20

Do you care? Does he care? I certainly don=E2=80=99t care.
  [5]
=C2=A0The spam bots became such a  transparent pretext for Musk to try to g=
et out of his deal to buy Twitter Inc. that I feel like everyone has been t=
rying to forget about them since the deal closed. Still, the Wall Street Jo=
urnal checks in:

Fake and spam accounts remain a persistent problem on Twitter, even as new =
owner Elon Musk has taken steps to stamp them out.
Several researchers say such accounts are still easy to find on the social-=
media platform. By at least one measure, the degree of bot activity after M=
usk took over in October was consistent with its level before.
=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s clearly the case that bad bots remain pervasive on Tw=
itter,=E2=80=9D said Jonathan Mayer, an assistant professor of computer sci=
ence at Princeton University who co-wrote a recent monthslong study of the =
platform and observed heavy bot-like behavior throughout.
Musk said last month that Twitter has eliminated at least 90% of scams on T=
witter, telling attendees at The Wall Street Journal=E2=80=99s CEO Council =
that there has been =E2=80=9Cdramatic improvement=E2=80=9D in Twitter=E2=80=
=99s ability to detect and remove troll armies.
There is no universal definition of fake or spam accounts, and determining =
a precise, authoritative number on a platform as big as Twitter is difficul=
t.

OH DETERMINING A PRECISE, AUTHORITATIVE NUMBER OF SPAM BOTS ON TWITTER IS D=
IFFICULT, IS IT? I am  going to go insane if I think about this for another=
 second. Though if you are one of the minority investors in Musk=E2=80=99s =
private Twitter, and you want to sue him for securities fraud for saying th=
at he eliminated 90% of spam bots, (1) you will not win, (2) it will probab=
ly destroy your life but (3) it will be very funny, to me.

