10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Friday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Western Alliance</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/31793244.260412/aHR0cHM6Ly9zb2NpYWxzY2llbmNlcy5tY21hc3R=
lci5jYS9lY29uL3VnY20vM2xsMy9iYWdlaG90L2xvbWJhcmQuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBa12aa321" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">Every banker knows</a> that if he has to prove that=
 he is worthy of credit, however good may be his arguments, in fact his cre=
dit is gone,=E2=80=9D but here=E2=80=99s this:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bleeding stopped only after the bank offer=
ed some major depositors a look inside its operations in exchange for signi=
ng nondisclosure arrangements. Some took up on the offer.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI feel for the depositors =E2=80=94 t=
hey didn=E2=80=99t sign up to be bank equity analysts,=E2=80=9D Mr. Gibbons=
 said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is from a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/31793244.260412/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vM=
jAyMy8wNi8xNC9idXNpbmVzcy93ZXN0ZXJuLWFsbGlhbmNlLXJlZ2lvbmFsLWJhbmtzLmh0bWw/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3a58ba87" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> New York Times story</a>=C2=A0b=
y Rob Copeland=C2=A0about how Western Alliance Bancorp weathered this year=
=E2=80=99s regional banking crisis, in which depositors got nervous about t=
he balance sheets of many smaller banks and started pulling their money out=
. And Western Alliance=E2=80=99s approach was, roughly, that=C2=A0people sh=
owed up to take their money out, and chief financial officer Dale Gibbons p=
ulled them into a room and said =E2=80=9Clook, don=E2=80=99t share this wit=
h anyone, but here is everything we know about our business, we=E2=80=99re =
gonna walk through our loans one by one to satisfy you that we are solvent =
so you leave your money here.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s like the=C2=A0<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31793244.260412/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cueW91dHViZS5jb20vd2F0Y2g_dj1pUGtKSDZCVDdkTQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
689d43fb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;"><em>It=E2=80=99s a Wonderful Life </em>bank run=C2=A0scen=
e</a>, except that instead of saying =E2=80=9Cthe money=E2=80=99s not here,=
 why your money=E2=80=99s in Joe=E2=80=99s house, that=E2=80=99s right next=
 to yours, and in the Kennedy house, and Mrs. Maitland=E2=80=99s house, and=
 a hundred others,=E2=80=9D George Bailey pulls each depositor aside and sa=
ys =E2=80=9Cthe money=E2=80=99s not here, why your money=E2=80=99s in Joe=
=E2=80=99s house, he=E2=80=99s got a 730 FICO and has never missed a paymen=
t and prices are up 14% in his neighborhood so the LTV is now at 63%, and i=
n the Kennedy house, and Kennedy just got a raise at work so his payments a=
re now down to 23% of his income, and Mrs. Maitland=E2=80=99s=E2=80=9D unti=
l the depositors=E2=80=99 eyes glaze over and they say =E2=80=9Cokay fine,=
=C2=A0whatever, I=E2=80=99ll leave my money here.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You see Bagehot=E2=80=99s point, though. If yo=
ur bank is sitting you down and making you sign a nondisclosure agreement t=
o tell you details of its operations=C2=A0<em>to keep your deposits</em>, s=
omething has gone very wrong. Not necessarily with the bank =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
apparently what Western Alliance=E2=80=99s depositors saw satisfied them th=
at the bank was fine,=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/31793244.260412/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYX=
RhLzEyMTI1NDUvMDAwMTIxMjU0NTIzMDAwMTI5L3dhbF8ycTIzaW52ZXN0b3JwcmVzeGZpbi5od=
G0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4bfab996" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">deposits stabilized</a> and t=
he stock is up =E2=80=94=C2=A0but with general confidence in the banking sy=
stem.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is the basic problem of regional banks. B=
ank depositors didn=E2=80=99t sign up to be bank equity analysts. Bank depo=
sits are supposed to be <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/31793244.260412/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDUvYmFuay1zdG9ja3MtbG9vay13b3JzZS10aGFuLWJhbmtzLWRvP2NtcGlk=
PUJCRDA2MTQyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV=
0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDYxNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB1634f6e1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  information-insensitive</a>; a dollar in a =
bank account is just supposed to be worth a dollar. Nobody is supposed to s=
ign an NDA to review non-public financial information (or even flip through=
 a 10-K to read public financial information) just to open a bank account. =
But if you are not conducting detailed due diligence on your bank, how do y=
ou know that your deposits at the bank are safe?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You are, in essence, trusting=C2=A0<em>the ban=
king system</em>, which often means trusting=C2=A0<em>the government=E2=80=
=99s regulation and supervision of banks</em>. In the US, if you have $250,=
000 or less in the bank,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important;=
 background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0you are pretty explicitly trusting the government: The US Federal=
 Deposit Insurance Corp. insures all bank deposits up to $250,000 per depos=
itor per bank, so you don=E2=80=99t really need to care about how good or b=
ad your bank=E2=80=99s business is. If you have much more than $250,000 in =
the bank, then your trust in the system and the government is more implicit=
 and vibes-based. =E2=80=9CThe US government wouldn=E2=80=99t let me lose a=
ll the money that I need to run my business,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cthe US go=
vernment wouldn=E2=80=99t let the banking system collapse,=E2=80=9D or =E2=
=80=9Cthe US banking system is highly regulated and politically salient, an=
d surely the US government would not allow my bank to take dumb risks with =
my money, so I=E2=80=99m sure its balance sheet is fine and I won=E2=80=99t=
 bother looking at it.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnot=
e-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !imp=
ortant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so the government is in charge of making s=
ure all the banks are fine. There are problems with this. One is that there=
 are a lot of banks, and it is hard for the government to know what they=E2=
=80=99re all up to.=C2=A0Another problem is that the many small banks,=C2=
=A0<em>because they are smaller</em>, are regulated less strictly than the =
few big banks:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These lenders have long pitched themselves as =
the crux of the U.S. economy, doling out loans and financing to small busin=
esses that would otherwise be ignored. They hold roughly two-thirds of all =
deposits in rural areas.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These banks receive relatively lax treatment f=
rom regulators, who require them to disclose less about their finances and =
set aside less money as a buffer against deposit runs, compared with their =
larger counterparts.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A third problem is moral hazard: There are 4,1=
00 banks and, before this year, most depositors kind of thought they were e=
qually safe, because the depositors weren=E2=80=99t doing any due diligence=
. And the government regulates them all to make sure that they behave prude=
ntly, but with 4,100 banks the government can only pay so much attention to=
 any one regional bank. If you are a bank, the more risk you take, the more=
 money you can make, and you can invest some of that money in attracting de=
posits (by paying higher deposit rates, or by doing more marketing, or by m=
aking loans and providing services to build relationships that bring in dep=
osits). If everyone is treated as equally risky, there is a tendency for de=
posits to flow to the riskiest banks. Copeland=E2=80=99s article begins wit=
h this horrifying anecdote:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Every quarter for the past several years, Ken =
Vecchione printed out a spreadsheet comparing the growth of the bank he run=
s, Western Alliance, with its three principal competitors: First Republic, =
Signature Bank and Silicon Valley Bank.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And each time, Mr. Vecchione was annoyed becau=
se the analysis would show that Western Alliance=E2=80=99s loans and deposi=
ts were growing similarly to the others =E2=80=94 its total assets tripled =
in five years =E2=80=94 but its stock price wasn=E2=80=99t soaring as high.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe were, I have to admit, a bit envio=
us of them,=E2=80=9D said Mr. Vecchione, who has been chief executive of th=
e Phoenix bank since 2018.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">First Republic, Signature and Silicon Valley B=
ank are all gone now: If you are a bank and you are growing faster than oth=
er banks, there=E2=80=99s a pretty good chance that it=E2=80=99s because yo=
u=E2=80=99re taking more risk than other banks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Vecchione =E2=80=9Csaid he had been asking reg=
ulators lately, =E2=80=98Do you even want us to exist?=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D It=
=E2=80=99s a fair question<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importan=
t; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>:=C2=A0</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Government officials can=E2=80=99t seem to dec=
ide what they want banks like Western Alliance to do. Since the 2008 financ=
ial crisis, policymakers have put the brakes on =E2=80=9Ctoo big to fail=E2=
=80=9D institutions, saying they would prefer risk to be distributed more e=
venly across lenders. Now, though, there is skepticism about the grow-at-al=
l-costs ambitions of smaller banks, and hints of an openness to mergers bet=
ween lenders.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a private meeting last month with bank chie=
fs, including Jamie Dimon of JPMorgan, Treasury Secretary Janet L. Yellen s=
aid she would welcome more lenders merging with one another, according to a=
 person who participated in the briefing, in part because it would make it =
easier for regulators to conduct oversight.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After 2008, there was a perception that the go=
vernment was implicitly guaranteeing the biggest banks, and that this was b=
ad; the reaction was to regulate the biggest banks more strictly, to try to=
 prevent them from becoming bigger, and to favor smaller regional banks. Af=
ter the 2023 crisis, there is a realization that=C2=A0<em>the government is=
 implicitly guaranteeing all of the banks</em>. And if you are in that busi=
ness anyway, you will prefer to guarantee a few big, well-capitalized, clos=
ely supervised banks rather than thousands of risky ones.</p>
